The "ape car" to avoid collisions
In the context of the development of accident prevention technologies, Nissan inspired himself this time, to nature, and in particular to bees.
Japanese society has created a robot that, by taking the flight of bees for example, knows how to avoid accidents.
It is the Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C, the first step towards collision prevention technologies.
The engineers of the Advanced Technical Center of Nissan Motor Co. have developed this small robot in collaboration with the Scientific and Technological Research Centre of the prestigious University of Tokyo in Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, Director General of Public Relations for Technology and Research and Development of Brand Management, BR23C is an expansion of the Security Shield of four areas produced by Nissan.
This robot is designed to improve the ability to prevent collisions in the home vehicle.
During the flight, each api creates its own personal oval-shaped space which is very similar to the Nissan security shield.
But the most important thing is the compound eyes of the bees, able to see in all directions with a angle above 300 degrees, and allowing the insect to fly continuously in its personal space.
To recreate this visual functionality, engineers have developed what they have defined as a localization laser (Laser Range Finder).
This mechanism identifies the obstacles facing the BR23C for a radius within two meters and with a maximum width of 180 degrees, calculates the distance from the object and sends a signal to a microprocessor on board that immediately allows for prevention of collision.
"At the moment when an obstacle is detected, the little robot imitates the movements of a bee and immediately changes direction by turning on the wheels at straight angle or larger to avoid collision.
The most obvious difference with any assisted system is that the escape maneuver is totally instinctive.
"If not, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, Director of the Mobility Laboratory and Chief Engineer of this project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot deflect upwards or downwards, and not diagonally; it can only move in two dimensions and in the direction in which they can turn its wheels and not exploit endless directions and ways as the bees do.
For this reason, Nissan has used a rotation function, in addition to acceleration and deceleration, so that the small robot can avoid collisions.
"This device only needs to process the information every few seconds, and to act on this data.
It does not require the storage of information or intuitive logic of previous maneuvers, so it can work without interruption and with only a few dozen KB of memory.
This may surprise, but we're not talking about memory gigabytes, and not even mega."
This is the first step towards the development of new technologies for the instant prevention of collisions, a technology that Nissan hopes will be serious in cars within ten years.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries, which are lighter and more durable than the lithium ion typology.
Another potential future application of this technology could be the integration of the units with a GPS satellite navigation system to bring the driver to destination avoiding the obstacles present in the route.
