The Benelux governments nationalize part of the Fortis bank
The Benelux states are helping through partial nationalisation the Belgian-Dutch bank Fortis, which was first in difficulty in Europe for the crisis of the American credit market: the three nations will provide EUR 11.2 billion to the financial institution - insurance with interests also in Hungary.
The governments of Belgium, Luxembourg and the Netherlands on the weekend agreed at the highest level, including the President of the European Central Bank and the European Commissioner for Competition.
In the euro area the first major crisis in the context of the difficulties in which the international financial market has been debated for more than a year is that of the Fortis bank, and from a certain point of view the decisions taken in this respect may constitute a precedent.
According to the decision taken on Sunday night all three states will own almost half (49%) of the bank's share in the country.
The bank will almost certainly sell part of its interests, including first of all the assets, especially insurance, of the Dutch ABN Amro acquired a year ago.
Last week the actions of Fortis had begun with a vertical collapse, serious signs of the institution's crisis had then appeared in the second half of the week.
However, analysts agree that the bank, with 85,000 employees, is too large to allow it to go bankrupt.
The bank's shares on Friday fell by almost 12%, the lowest point for 14 years.
Since January the value of the shares has decreased by more than two thirds.
Considering the current stock prices the entire group's capital value is around EUR 14 billion, but according to bank managers this value is not real.
The corporate summit blames the collapse of the Fortis shares on the uncertainties of the extra-European market due to the acceptance of the US plan of 700 billion dollars.
On Monday the title resumed slowly to rise.
Friday Filip Dierckx was appointed new managing director of the bank.
The financial institution has also sought private buyers but so far no one has presented itself with a worthy offer.
The Belgian Government had already ensured that investors should not fear losing money.
Among the bank's customers there was no panic, the branches were not visited.
In Hungary Fortis owns autonomous subsidiaries and has also purchased leasing companies.
The fox in the chicken
In America, life and health insurers often refuse to enter into an insurance contract on the basis of people's medical purchase data.
Privacy experts fear that the data market becomes uncontrollable.
"There is a privacy program that the use of prescription data depends in any case on the approval of the person concerned.
This program must be in independent hands, otherwise it is like entrusting the chicken to the fox" - writes the Washington Post citing Richard Dick as the author of the program to follow the prescriptions of the medicines.
Insurance companies are subject to the insurance rate and the relevant figure in the case of health claims of the potential customer and if they consider the risk too high they do not stipulate the insurance.
Some time ago the customer had to undergo a medical visit and the contract was concluded only after the outcome of the examination.
Dick 10 years ago invented a much cheaper procedure: according to the customer's identification code you can easily have information from the pharmacy about which medicines you bought in the last year and half and from this the evince program of which diseases you suffer and what health conditions you are in.
For example, if you regularly buy large amounts of cholesterol reducers this means that the level of fat in the blood is in practice irrevocably high and is classified into the highest risk category.
There are various versions of the programme on the market, some of which also determine the risk multiplier, so the insurer does not remain much more than paper work, even if there are small difficulties.
Among the counters are that some medicines are usable for more purposes, e.g. some compounds are usable against migraine or heat vapours, but they are also effective against depression.
The latter, from an insurance - commercial point of view, is as a risk increase factor, the first two no.
For the request and processing of data, companies were formed separately and these, before obtaining the necessary information from the pharmacy, require the patient's approval.
Now the authorities force them to do so even if so far they have not imposed fines on negligence.
Some companies have also developed the results of laboratory tests and linked them to medical consumption data in order to provide a more accurate picture of the patient's health status.
More and more companies have access to data and parallel use control will be increasingly difficult.
There is a separate privacy law but its validity extends only to health services and insurance.
In front of the Congress there is a proposal for a law that gives control authority competence to specialized companies in data service.
Richard Dick admits that it is not enough: for this reason he has developed a program that links the other data with the approval expressed by the person concerned.
Another question is that the person concerned cannot deny approval because otherwise insurers do not enter into the contract.
So then in the end the hens are entrusted to the mercy of the fox.
